column278: In the beginning I tried to only put about 10% on A and most of it on B. I liked the last part of it where we could see how other participants were doing. It made it feel more like a game and made me want to take more risks. I felt that the 4% to win $20 was not a good decision to make and so I decided not to choose that very often. I didn't quite understand how we lost money.
You need to take risks to get rewards and sometimes it really paid off but sometimes it back fired.

60% in the safe account typically  tried some rounds with 40% safe. Results seemed better with more in the safe account  though porbability dictates the risky account should give a higher overall return. Last few rounds I bet it all  the averages told me it was exactly the same as my score  not sure how this was possible. I only continued such risky betting because the average was the same as my score. Was this a bug/trick?
Stressful! I tried to see a pattern which failed me at some of the worst times. Experiment was very clear.

I decided to go all in for the beginning rounds and try to keep about $3 invested into asset A  since 3% of $3 seemed paltry. As long as my total account was less than $3  I'd continue investing all into A. After a big payoff  I'd start saving into B. The amount in B was usually determined by the amount in A (starting from $3  then increasing by a dollar or so after large payoffs  but keeping the amount in B stable after losses). I also tried to invest into asset B by taking advantage of the 3% rounding  so I tried to get as close to 34  67  and 00 cents as possible.

In the beginning of each path  I started by investing just under half my money each round. If I got more than $10  I tried to avoid gambling more than $5-ish in any given period. I don't really know anything about finances or investment  so I was just making things up.
It seemed as if the mean of Asset A returns were below 6%. I did not understand the function of Asset C  that the lottery only applied for 1 period.
I tried to take chances and but when I had a lot of money I would take less chances
It was fun. Kind of monotonous and boring halfway through though.

I always decided how much money I was unwilling to lose based on the amount I had earned so far. In the beginning of each period  I would bet in a more risky fashion than near the end on average  since $3 wasn't much to lose. Near the middle and end of the period  I would think "how much do I want to guarantee myself walking away with?" and place this amount into "B". In general  I would describe myself as not a big risk taker.
